ation|Target]] exclusive) / November 11, 2014 (wide retail)<br>'''Episodes''': \"For Your Ice Only\" (175),  \"Happy New Year!\" (176), \"Terrifying Tri-State Trilogy of Terror\" (200), \"Steampunx\" (203), \"Father's Day\" (208), \"It's No Picnic\" (211), \"Star Wars\" (215), \"Tales from the Resistance: Back to the 2nd Dimension\" (219) and \"Doof 101\" (220)\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist | group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n<!-- Do not include tv.com episode lists here. Tv.com is not a reliable source for episode information. -->\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Tv.com episodes|phineas-and-ferb|69897|Phineas and Ferb|3}}\n\n{{Phineas and Ferb}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phineas And Ferb}}\n[[Category:2012 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2013 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2014 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2015 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Phineas and Ferb episodes| ]]\n", "name_user": "197.204.17.166", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phineas_and_Ferb_(season_4)"}
{"title_page": "Inner Mongolia incident", "text_new": "{{About|a purge during the Cultural Revolution|the incident in 2011|2011 Inner Mongolia unrest}}\n{{Infobox Chinese |order=st\n|s=\u5185\u4eba\u515a\u4e8b\u4ef6 |t=\u5167\u4eba\u9ee8\u4e8b\u4ef6\n  |p=n\u00e8ir\u00e9nd\u01ceng sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n|altname = Inner Mongolia People's Revolution Party purge incident\n|s2=\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u515a\u8083\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6 |t2=\u5167\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u9ee8\u8085\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6\n  |p2=N\u00e8im\u011bngg\u01d4 r\u00e9nm\u00edn g\u00e9m\u00ecngd\u01ceng s\u00f9q\u012bng sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n}}\nThe '''Inner Mongolia incident''' ({{zh|s=\u5185\u4eba\u515a\u4e8b\u4ef6}}), or '''Inner Mongolia People's Revolution Party purge incident''' ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u515a\u8083\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6}}), was a massive [[Purge|political purge]] during the [[Cultural Revolution]] in [[Inner Mongolia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmg.xinhuanet.com/bnfynmg/bnbs/zzp/zz36.htm |script-title=zh:\u5341\u5e74\u6d69\u52ab\u4e2d\u7684\u5185\u8499\u53e4|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Xinhuanet]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> The purge was supported by the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] and was led by [[Teng Haiqing]], a [[Lieutenant general|lieutenant general (zhong jiang)]] of the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Kerry|date=2007-07-01|title=The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia 1967\u20131969: The Purge of the \"Heirs of Genghis Khan\"|journal=Asian Affairs|volume=38|issue=2|pages=173\u2013187|doi=10.1080/03068370701349128|issn=0306-8374}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ccr-sm.net/215/|title=\"The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia\" by Paul Hyer and William Heaton|last=|first=|date=|website=\u5185\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u3068\u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> It took place from 1967-1969 during which over a million people were categorized as members of the already-dissolved [[Inner Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]] (PRP), while [[lynching]] and direct [[massacre]] resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands, most of whom were [[Mongols]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976|title=Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|website=www.sciencespo.fr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://mjlsh.usc.cuhk.edu.hk/Book.aspx?cid=4&tid=4510|script-title=zh:\"\u5185\u4eba\u515a\"\u51a4\u6848\u524d\u540e|last=Bai|first=Yintai|date=|website=Chinese University of Hong Kong|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://beijingspring.com/bj2/1996/240/2003125153343.htm |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u4e4b\u6625---\u6587\u9769[\u5185\u4eba\u515a]\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7aa5\u63a2|author=|date=|publisher=\u5df4\u8d6b|accessdate=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAccording to the official [[complaint]] from the [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] in 1980 after the Cultural Revolution, during the purge, 346 thousand people were arrested, over 16 thousand were persecuted to death or killed directly, and over 81 thousand were permanently injured and [[disabled]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT477&lpg=PT477&dq=%E5%86%85%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%9A+%E5%B7%B4%E8%B5%AB#v=onepage&q=%E5%86%85%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%9A%20%E5%B7%B4%E8%B5%AB&f=false |script-title=zh:\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|last=Yang|first=Jishen|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/military-06052011183520.html|title=Inner Mongolia in 'War-Like State'|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Other estimates have put a death toll between 20 thousand and 100 thousand, while hundreds of thousands were arrested and persecuted, and over a million people were affected.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/mongolian-historian-07232018123931.html|title=China Holds Ethnic Mongolian Historian Who Wrote 'Genocide' Book|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://madeinchinajournal.com/2019/01/18/grassroots-turmoil-in-chinas-cultural-revolution-a-half-century-perspective/|title=Turmoil at the Grassroots in China's Cultural Revolution: A Half-Century Perspective|last=Unger|first=Jonathan|date=2019-01-18|website=Made in China Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Cultural Revolution, the purge was regarded as a \"mistake\" and its victims were rehabilitated by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC), but the commander of the purge, Teng Haiqing, received no [[trial]] or legal punishment at all because the Central Committee of CPC thought he had made achievements during the wars in the past.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BkLADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&lpg=PA80&dq=%E6%BB%95%E6%B5%B7%E6%B8%85+%E6%9C%AA%E5%8F%97%E5%88%B0#v=onepage&q=%E6%BB%95%E6%B5%B7%E6%B8%85%20%E6%9C%AA%E5%8F%97%E5%88%B0&f=false |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u5b66\u4eba\u8bba\u6587\u96c6\u2014\u2014\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d50\u5e74\uff081-4\uff09: \u6587\u732e\u4e0e\u7efc\u8ff0\uff08\u4e00\uff09|last=\u542f\u4e4b|date=2019-11-26|publisher=Remembering Publishing, LLC|isbn=978-1-951135-05-8|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{lang|zh-Hans|\u300a\u4e4c\u5170\u5df4\u5e72\u6848\u5377\u300b\u5185\u8499\u653f\u6cd5\u59d4\u4f1a\u8bae\u8bb0\u5f55}}, May 1987 {{in lang|zh}}</ref> On the other hand, some of Teng's affiliates received various [[Term of imprisonment|terms of imprisonment]], with a main Mongol affiliate sentenced to 15 years in prison.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smhric.org/IMPRP.pdf |script-title=zh:\u6316\u8083\u707e\u96be\u5b9e\u5f55|last=Ba|first=Yantai|date=|website=|publisher=Southern Mongolian Human Rights Information Center|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical background ==\n[[File:Ulanhu1955.jpg|thumb|249x249px|Ulanhu, the founding Chairman of China's [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], was persecuted.]]\nOn May 16, 1966, the [[Cultural Revolution]] was officially launched. From June 7 to July 20, [[Ulanhu]], then the Chairman of China's [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], was widely criticized as an \"anti-Party activist\" and persecuted.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was also criticized by central leaders like [[Liu Shaoqi]] and [[Deng Xiaoping]], whom themselves were soon persecuted in the Revolution.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{lang|zh-Hans|\u300a\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u3001\u9093\u5c0f\u5e73\u4e0e\u4e4c\u5170\u592b\u7684\u8c08\u8bdd\u8bb0\u5f55\u300b\u2014\u2014\u300a\u6587\u9769\u8d44\u6599\u300b\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u515a\u59d4\u673a\u5173\u7ea2\u65d7\u8054\u5408\u603b\u90e81967\u5e748\u6708\u7f16\u5370}}</ref> On the 16th of August, Ulanhu was dismissed from his positions and was [[House arrest|house-arrested]] in [[Beijing]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn May, 1967, [[Teng Haiqing]] became the leader of the Inner Mongolia Military Region.<ref name=\":1\" /> On July 27, 1967, the northern branch of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] announced that Ulanhu had conducted five crimes, including anti-[[Maoism|Maosim]], anti-[[socialism]], [[separatism]], and so on.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e2d\u5171\u4e2d\u592e\u6279\u8f6c\u4e4c\u5170\u592b\u9519\u8bef\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u62a5\u544a\u2014\u2014\uff08\u4e2d\u53d1<67>31\u53f71967\u5e741\u670827\u65e5\uff09}}</ref> Supported by [[Lin Biao]], [[Jiang Qing]] and [[Kang Sheng]], a massive movement intended to \"dig out\" the \"poison of Ulanhu\" was then carried out in Inner Mongolia.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nDuring the movement, the already-dissolved [[Inner Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]] (PRP) was claimed to have re-established itself and grown into power since 1960.<ref name=\":1\" /> At least hundreds of thousands of people were categorized as the members of the PRP, whom were regarded as [[Separatism|separatists]] and were persecuted.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Mongolian language was banned from publications and Mongols were accused of being  \u201cthe sons and heirs of [[Genghis Khan]]\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Lynching and massacre ==\n\n=== Methods of torturing and killing ===\n[[File:Tenghaiqing.jpg|thumb|245x245px|Lieutenant general [[Teng Haiqing]] was the commander of the Inner Mongolia purge.]]\nThe methods used in lynching and killing during the purge included branding with hot irons, feeding [[furnace]] wastes, removing livers, [[hanging]], cutting tongues and noses, piercing nails, piercing vaginas, pouring hot [[saline water]] into wounds, and more.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Death toll ===\nAccording to the official [[complaint]] from the [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] in 1980 after the Cultural Revolution, during the purge, 346 thousand people were arrested (75 percent were Mongols), over 16 thousand were persecuted to death, and over 81 thousand were permanently injured and [[disabled]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nOther estimates include:\n\n* According to scholar Ba He ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5df4\u8d6b}}): close to 100 thousand people were killed, 700-800 thousand were arrested and persecuted, and over a million were affected.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*According to historian Song Yongyi ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5}}) of the [[California State University, Los Angeles]]: an unofficial source points out that the death toll was at least 40,000; 140,000 reached the point of permanent deformity, and nearly 700,000 were persecuted.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* According to historian Lhamjab A. Borjigin ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u62c9\u5e55\u672d\u90e8}}), who were arrested and prosecuted by the Chinese government in 2019 for conducting relevant researches: at least 27,900 were killed and 346,000 were imprisoned and tortured.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/author-09162019110051.html|title=Ethnic Mongolian Author Sentenced, Placed Under 'Community Correction' Order|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable figures killed ===\n\n* [[Ji Yatai]], 1st Ambassador of the [[People's Republic of China]] to [[Mongolia]] (1950\u20131953) and Vice-chairman of [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]].\n*Ha Fenge, Vice-chairman of [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]]. \n* [[Darijaya]], Vice-chairman of the Government of Inner Mongolia.\n\n== Rehabilitation ==\nAfter the Cultural Revolution, China's new [[paramount leader]] [[Deng Xiaoping]] came to power in 1978 and directed, together with [[Hu Yaobang]] and others, a large-scale rehabilitation of mistaken cases and false cases made during the Revolution.\n\nThe Inner Mongolia incident was regarded as a \"mistake\" and was rehabilitated by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC) in 1979, blaming the entire purge on \u201cthe [[Gang of Four]] and the Lin Biao Clique\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Trials for the Gang of Four started in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/gangoffour/Gangof4.html|title=Gang of Four Trial|website=law2.umkc.edu|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, in the 1980s, there were calls for trial of Teng Haiqing, the commander of the purge, but the Central Committee of CPC thought Teng had made achievements during the wars in the past and he would not have to take responsibility for the purge.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> On the other hand, some of Teng's affiliates received various [[Term of imprisonment|terms of imprisonment]], with a main Mongol affiliate, Wu'er Bagan ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4e4c\u5170\u5df4\u5e72}}), sentenced to 15 years in prison.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[List of massacres in China]]\n* [[Cultural Revolution]]\n*[[Cleansing the Class Ranks]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Yang Haiying. ''The Truth about the Mongolian Genocide during the Chinese Cultural Revolution.'' Asian Studies, Special Issue 6, Shizuoka University. March 2017.\n*Paul Hyer and William Heaton. ''The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia''. The China Quarterly, No. 36 (Oct. - Dec., 1968), pp.&nbsp;114\u2013128\n\n[[Category:Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by China]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Inner Mongolia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a purge during the Cultural Revolution|the incident in 2011|2011 Inner Mongolia unrest}}\n{{Infobox Chinese |order=st\n|s=\u5185\u4eba\u515a\u4e8b\u4ef6 |t=\u5167\u4eba\u9ee8\u4e8b\u4ef6\n  |p=n\u00e8ir\u00e9nd\u01ceng sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n|altname = Inner Mongolia People's Revolution Party purge incident\n|s2=\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u515a\u8083\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6 |t2=\u5167\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u9ee8\u8085\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6\n  |p2=N\u00e8im\u011bngg\u01d4 r\u00e9nm\u00edn g\u00e9m\u00ecngd\u01ceng s\u00f9q\u012bng sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n}}\nThe '''Inner Mongolia incident''' ({{zh|s=\u5185\u4eba\u515a\u4e8b\u4ef6}}), or '''Inner Mongolia People's Revolution Party purge incident''' ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u4eba\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u515a\u8083\u6e05\u4e8b\u4ef6}}), was a massive [[Purge|political purge]] during the [[Cultural Revolution]] in [[Inner Mongolia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmg.xinhuanet.com/bnfynmg/bnbs/zzp/zz36.htm |script-title=zh:\u5341\u5e74\u6d69\u52ab\u4e2d\u7684\u5185\u8499\u53e4|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Xinhuanet]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> The purge was supported by the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] and was led by [[Teng Haiqing]], a [[Lieutenant general|lieutenant general (zhong jiang)]] of the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Kerry|date=2007-07-01|title=The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia 1967\u20131969: The Purge of the \"Heirs of Genghis Khan\"|journal=Asian Affairs|volume=38|issue=2|pages=173\u2013187|doi=10.1080/03068370701349128|issn=0306-8374}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ccr-sm.net/215/|title=\"The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia\" by Paul Hyer and William Heaton|last=|first=|date=|website=\u5185\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u3068\u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> It took place from 1967-1969 during which over a million people were categorized as members of the already-dissolved [[Inner Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]] (PRP), while [[lynching]] and direct [[massacre]] resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands, most of whom were [[Mongols]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976|title=Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|website=www.sciencespo.fr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://mjlsh.usc.cuhk.edu.hk/Book.aspx?cid=4&tid=4510|script-title=zh:\"\u5185\u4eba\u515a\"\u51a4\u6848\u524d\u540e|last=Bai|first=Yintai|date=|website=Chinese University of Hong Kong|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://beijingspring.com/bj2/1996/240/2003125153343.htm |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u4e4b\u6625---\u6587\u9769[\u5185\u4eba\u515a]\u4e8b\u4ef6\u7aa5\u63a2|author=|date=|publisher=\u5df4\u8d6b|accessdate=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAccording to the official [[complaint]] from the [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] in 1980 after the Cultural Revolution, during the purge, 346 thousand people were arrested, over 16 thousand were persecuted to death or killed directly, and over 81 thousand were permanently injured and [[disabled]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT477&lpg=PT477&dq=%E5%86%85%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%9A+%E5%B7%B4%E8%B5%AB#v=onepage&q=%E5%86%85%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%9A%20%E5%B7%B4%E8%B5%AB&f=false |script-title=zh:\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|last=Yang|first=Jishen|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/military-06052011183520.html|title=Inner Mongolia in 'War-Like State'|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Other estimates have put a death toll between 20 thousand and 100 thousand, while hundreds of thousands were arrested and persecuted, and over a million people were affected.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/mongolian-historian-07232018123931.html|title=China Holds Ethnic Mongolian Historian Who Wrote 'Genocide' Book|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://madeinchinajournal.com/2019/01/18/grassroots-turmoil-in-chinas-cultural-revolution-a-half-century-perspective/|title=Turmoil at the Grassroots in China's Cultural Revolution: A Half-Century Perspective|last=Unger|first=Jonathan|date=2019-01-18|website=Made in China Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Cultural Revolution, the purge was regarded as a \"mistake\" and its victims were rehabilitated by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC), but the commander of the purge, Teng Haiqing, received no [[trial]] or legal punishment at all because the Central Committee of CPC thought he had made achievements during the wars in the past.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BkLADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&lpg=PA80&dq=%E6%BB%95%E6%B5%B7%E6%B8%85+%E6%9C%AA%E5%8F%97%E5%88%B0#v=onepage&q=%E6%BB%95%E6%B5%B7%E6%B8%85%20%E6%9C%AA%E5%8F%97%E5%88%B0&f=false |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u5b66\u4eba\u8bba\u6587\u96c6\u2014\u2014\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d50\u5e74\uff081-4\uff09: \u6587\u732e\u4e0e\u7efc\u8ff0\uff08\u4e00\uff09|last=\u542f\u4e4b|date=2019-11-26|publisher=Remembering Publishing, LLC|isbn=978-1-951135-05-8|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{lang|zh-Hans|\u300a\u4e4c\u5170\u5df4\u5e72\u6848\u5377\u300b\u5185\u8499\u653f\u6cd5\u59d4\u4f1a\u8bae\u8bb0\u5f55}}, May 1987 {{in lang|zh}}</ref> On the other hand, some of Teng's affiliates received various [[Term of imprisonment|terms of imprisonment]], with a main Mongol affiliate sentenced to 15 years in prison.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smhric.org/IMPRP.pdf |script-title=zh:\u6316\u8083\u707e\u96be\u5b9e\u5f55|last=Ba|first=Yantai|date=|website=|publisher=Southern Mongolian Human Rights Information Center|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical background ==\n[[File:Ulanhu1955.jpg|thumb|249x249px|Ulanhu, the founding Chairman of China's [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], was persecuted.]]\nOn May 16, 1966, the [[Cultural Revolution]] was officially launched. From June 7 to July 20, [[Ulanhu]], then the Chairman of China's [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], was widely criticized as an \"anti-Party activist\" and persecuted.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was also criticized by central leaders like [[Liu Shaoqi]] and [[Deng Xiaoping]], whom themselves were soon persecuted in the Revolution.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{lang|zh-Hans|\u300a\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u3001\u9093\u5c0f\u5e73\u4e0e\u4e4c\u5170\u592b\u7684\u8c08\u8bdd\u8bb0\u5f55\u300b\u2014\u2014\u300a\u6587\u9769\u8d44\u6599\u300b\u5185\u8499\u53e4\u515a\u59d4\u673a\u5173\u7ea2\u65d7\u8054\u5408\u603b\u90e81967\u5e748\u6708\u7f16\u5370}}</ref> On the 16th of August, Ulanhu was dismissed from his positions and was [[House arrest|house-arrested]] in [[Beijing]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn May, 1967, [[Teng Haiqing]] became the leader of the Inner Mongolia Military Region.<ref name=\":1\" /> On July 27, 1967, the northern branch of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] announced that Ulanhu had conducted five crimes, including anti-[[Maoism|Maosim]], anti-[[socialism]], [[separatism]], and so on.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e2d\u5171\u4e2d\u592e\u6279\u8f6c\u4e4c\u5170\u592b\u9519\u8bef\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u62a5\u544a\u2014\u2014\uff08\u4e2d\u53d1<67>31\u53f71967\u5e741\u670827\u65e5\uff09}}</ref> Supported by [[Lin Biao]], [[Jiang Qing]] and [[Kang Sheng]], a massive movement intended to \"dig out\" the \"poison of Ulanhu\" was then carried out in Inner Mongolia.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nDuring the movement, the already-dissolved [[Inner Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]] (PRP) was claimed to have re-established itself and grown into power since 1960.<ref name=\":1\" /> At least hundreds of thousands of people were categorized as the members of the PRP, whom were regarded as [[Separatism|separatists]] and were persecuted.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Mongolian language was banned from publications and Mongols were accused of being  \u201cthe sons and heirs of [[Genghis Khan]]\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Lynching and massacre ==\n\n=== Methods of torturing and killing ===\n[[File:Tenghaiqing.jpg|thumb|245x245px|Lieutenant general [[Teng Haiqing]] was the commander of the Inner Mongolia purge.]]\nThe methods used in lynching and killing during the purge included branding with hot irons, feeding [[furnace]] wastes, removing livers, [[hanging]], cutting tongues and noses, piercing nails, piercing vaginas, pouring hot [[saline water]] into wounds, and more.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Death toll ===\nAccording to the official [[complaint]] from the [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] in 1980 after the Cultural Revolution, during the purge, 346 thousand people were arrested (75 percent were Mongols), over 16 thousand were persecuted to death, and over 81 thousand were permanently injured and [[disabled]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nOther estimates include:\n\n* According to scholar Ba He ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5df4\u8d6b}}): close to 100 thousand people were killed, 700-800 thousand were arrested and persecuted, and over a million were affected.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*According to historian Song Yongyi ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5}}) of the [[California State University, Los Angeles]]: an unofficial source points out that the death toll was at least 40,000; 140,000 reached the point of permanent deformity, and nearly 700,000 were persecuted.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* According to historian Lhamjab A. Borjigin ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u62c9\u5e55\u672d\u90e8}}), who were arrested and prosecuted by the Chinese government in 2019 for conducting relevant researches: at least 27,900 were killed and 346,000 were imprisoned and tortured.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/author-09162019110051.html|title=Ethnic Mongolian Author Sentenced, Placed Under 'Community Correction' Order|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable figures killed ===\n\n* [[Ji Yatai]], 1st Ambassador of the [[People's Republic of China]] to [[Mongolia]] (1950\u20131953) and Vice-chairman of [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]].\n*Ha Fenge, Vice-chairman of [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]]. \n* [[Darijaya]], Vice-chairman of the Government of Inner Mongolia.\n\n== Rehabilitation ==\nAfter the Cultural Revolution, China's new [[paramount leader]] [[Deng Xiaoping]] came to power in 1978 and directed, together with [[Hu Yaobang]] and others, a large-scale rehabilitation of mistaken cases and false cases made during the Revolution.\n\nThe Inner Mongolia incident was regarded as a \"mistake\" and was rehabilitated by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC) in 1979, blaming the entire purge on \u201cthe [[Gang of Four]] and the Lin Biao Clique\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Trials for the Gang of Four started in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/gangoffour/Gangof4.html|title=Gang of Four Trial|website=law2.umkc.edu|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, in the 1980s, there were calls for trial of Teng Haiqing, the commander of the purge, but the Central Committee of CPC thought Teng had made achievements during the wars in the past and he would not have to take responsibility for the purge.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> On the other hand, some of Teng's affiliates received various [[Term of imprisonment|terms of imprisonment]], with a main Mongol affiliate, Wu'er Bagan ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4e4c\u5170\u5df4\u5e72}}), sentenced to 15 years in prison.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[List of massacres in China]]\n* [[Cultural Revolution]]\n*[[Cleansing the Class Ranks]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Yang Haiying. ''The Truth about the Mongolian Genocide during the Chinese Cultural Revolution.'' Asian Studies, Special Issue 6, Shizuoka University. March 2017.\n*Paul Hyer and William Heaton. ''The Cultural Revolution in Inner Mongolia''. The China Quarterly, No. 36 (Oct. - Dec., 1968), pp.&nbsp;114\u2013128\n\n[[Category:Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by China]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n", "name_user": "SCreditC", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_Mongolia_incident"}
{"title_page": "Kirakira PreCure a la Mode", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name = Kirakira \u2606 PreCure a la Mode\n| image = Kirakiraprec.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption  = Cover of the final [[Blu-ray]] volume, featuring the six Cures. In clockwise order: Cure Chocolat, Cure Macaron, Cure Custard, Cure Whip, Cure Parfait and Cure Gelato in the center. \n| ja_kanji = \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\n| ja_romaji = Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo\n| genre = [[Magical girl]]\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type = tv series\n| director = Kohei Kureta<br>Yukio Kaizawa\n| producer = Akira Tanaka<br>Risa End\u014d<br>Yu Kaminoki\n| writer = Jin Tanaka\n| music = [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]]\n| studio = [[Toei Animation]]\n| licensee = \n| network =  [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] ([[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], [[TV Asahi]])\n| network_en = \n| first = February 5, 2017\n| last = January 28, 2018\n| episodes = 49\n| episode_list = List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Izumi Todo]]\n| illustrator     = [[Futago Kamikita]]\n| publisher       = [[Kodansha]]\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014djo manga|Sh\u014djo]]''\n| imprint         = ''Wide KC''\n| magazine        = [[Nakayoshi]]\n| first           = March 2017\n| last            = December 2017\n| volumes         = 2\n| volume_list     =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = [[KiraKira PreCure \u00e0 la Mode: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!|Kirakira PreCure a la Mode the Movie: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!<br />Petit\u2606Dream Stars! Let's\u30fbla\u30fbCookin'? Showtime!]]\n| director        = \n| producer        =\n| studio          = [[Toei Animation]]\n| released        = October 28, 2017\n| runtime         =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Kirakira PreCure a la Mode'''''|\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9|Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo|lit. \"Glittering Pretty Cure [[List of French expressions in English|\u00e0 la Mode]]\"|lead=yes}}, shortened as {{nihongo|'''''PreAla'''''|\u30d7\u30ea\u30a2\u30e9|PuriAra}}<ref group=note>Shortened term Toei used in official [[Twitter]] posts of the anime</ref> is a 2017 Japanese [[magical girl]] [[anime]] series produced by [[Toei Animation]] and the fourteenth installment in [[Izumi Todo]]'s ''[[Pretty Cure]]'' [[metaseries]], featuring the twelfth generation of Cures. It is directed by Kohei Kureta and Yukio Kaizawa. Jin Tanaka wrote the script, and Marie Ino designed the characters. The cake and sweets designs were handled by [[Pastry chef|p\u00e2tissi\u00e8re]] Junko Fukuda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/toeianime_info/status/813128054574759936|title=\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u516c\u5f0f on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> The series began airing on all [[All-Nippon News Network]] stations in [[Japan]] on February 5, 2017, succeeding ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!|Witchy PreCure!]]'' in its initial timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anime.eiga.com/news/103897/|title=\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d17\u5e742\u67085\u65e5\u653e\u9001\u958b\u59cb\u3000\u30c6\u30fc\u30de\u306f\u300c\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u300d\u3068\u300c\u30a2\u30cb\u30de\u30eb\u300d|publisher=}}</ref>  It was then succeeded by ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'' on February 4, 2018. The series' main topic is happiness, while [[desserts]] and [[animals]] serve as the motif.\n\n==Plot==\n{{See also|List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode characters}}\nIchika Usami is a second year middle school student who loves sweets and wishes to work in a patisserie, but struggles to make a good strawberry shortcake for her mother who was coming home from traveling around the world. One day, she encounters a fairy named Pekorin, who is able to detect \"kirakiraru\", an element residing in sweets that represent the feelings put into them. However, evil fairies start to steal the kirakiraru for themselves, leaving the sweets black and lifeless. Determined to protect the sweets, Ichika gains the power of the Legendary Patisserie and transforms into the Pretty Cure, Cure Whip, to protect the kirakiraru. Joined by five other Pretty Cures, Ichika opens up the mobile sweet shop, Kirakira Patisserie, and spends her days making sweets while fighting against those who seek to steal kirakiraru and bring misfortune to the world.<ref name=\"story\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/story/|title=\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30ea\u30fc\uff06\u30ad\u30fc\u30ef\u30fc\u30c9 - \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9-\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3:|publisher=Toei Animation|language=Japanese|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n==Production==\nThe series was first registered by Toei at the Japanese Copyright Office on October 25, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-10-25/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-trademark-filed/.108036|title='Kirakira Precure a la Mode' Trademark Filed|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> A month after registration, Toei opened a teaser site for the series with the catchphrase \"Create, Taste and Battle!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-27/toei-confirms-kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-tv-anime-for-2017/.109239|title=Toei Confirms Kirakira Precure a la Mode TV Anime for 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mantan-web.jp/2016/11/28/20161127dog00m200036000c.html|title=\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\uff1a\u7b2c14\u5f3e\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d\u304c17\u5e74\u6625\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30c8 \u3064\u304f\u3063\u3066\uff01\u305f\u3079\u3066\uff01\u305f\u305f\u304b\u3063\u3066\uff01|publisher=}}</ref> On December 26, 2016, Toei updated the official website with main characters and staff, alongside the two theme songs and the official release date, also marking as the third series in the franchise to utilize a 5-piece group. It was also confirmed that the main characters were all running a sweets shop<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moca-news.net/article/20161226/2016122606000a_/01/|title=TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u306f2\u67085\u65e5\uff08\u65e5\uff09\u653e\u9001\u958b\u59cb\u3002\u30ad\u30fc\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u30fb\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u8a2d\u5b9a\u306a\u3069\u3082\u89e3\u7981|publisher=moca}}</ref> and although it will still feature battle scenes like its predecessor, ''Kira Kira'' will have a different style of fight scenes called Colorful Pop Battles in order to fit with the series's theme.\n\nIn an interview with the team behind the series, they expressed a lot of concepts being used and adapted in the series. The producers stated that the 5-piece team concept was used after 10 years in order to differentiate it from the previous series, ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'' which uses the \"Buddy Concept\". The motif of the series was decided also by the producers due to the choices are being taken. Producer Yu Kaminoki said that \"Running a Sweets Shop/bakery is one of many girls have dreamed of when they grow up, and that is a good theme for the next series. However deciding on how fighting elements would fit in a Dessert-themed series is hard and is not compatible with Pretty Cure or any fighting girls series\" and also stated \"using Animals as a secondary morif could help balance the first motif of the series and is possible with imagination, to actually make the series work than just using Sweets as the series's motif\". Also, the producer said that \"Animal mofif would extend to the main character, Ichika, who decorates and creates desserts with an animal motif due to her huge imagination.\"<ref name=\"animate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1485843322&image_share=14|title=\u8089\u5f3e\u6226\u3092\u5c01\u5370\u3059\u308b\u3053\u3068\u3067\u63cf\u3051\u308b\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u3089\u3057\u3055\u304c\u3042\u308b\uff01\u3000\u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u795e\u6728\u512a\u30d7\u30ed\u30c7\u30e5\u30fc\u30b5\u30fc\uff06\u66ae\u7530\u516c\u5e73\uff33\uff24\uff06\u8c9d\u6fa4\u5e78\u7537\uff33\uff24\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|publisher=[[Animate]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile discussing the staff, the producer said that Kohei Kureta and Yukio Kaizawa were chosen to direct the series, as a way to lessen the burden in production due to coming up with newer concepts. Yukio Kaizawa was also chosen due to his work with ''Cure Flora and the Mischievous Mirror'' short film and that he said that he wanted to incorporate new ideas into the series as director. Kaizawa also stated that it was his first time to direct a series in Toei's Sunday morning lineup since joining the staff and that directing alongside Kohei Kureta would be a challenge. Kureta was grateful that he can work with him. Despite working together, both directors will direct the series in different episodes and both will have responsibility for how the series will turn out.<ref name=\"animate\"/>\n\nFor the characters, the staff made each of their personalities unique in order to match the animal motif of the series. The most unique one to stand out is Akira, in which the producers based her overall role to the {{nihongo|\"Otokoyaku|\u7537\u5f79||\"Male Role\"}} actresses of [[Takarazuka Revue]], a theatrical group owned by [[Hankyu Corporation]]. [[Nanako Mori]] said that her experience with the group in the past is the inspiration for her role in the anime and that playing a big sister in the series is a first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/news/2017020302.php|title=\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9 - \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9|author=|date=|work=toei-anim.co.jp|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n===Anime===\n{{see also|List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode episodes}}\nThe anime began airing on [[All-Nippon News Network]] stations in Japan, including [[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] and [[TV Asahi]], on February 5, 2017, replacing the previous series, ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'', in its initial timeslot.<ref name=\"dateannounce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-25/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-anime-reveals-february-5-debut-theme-songs-new-visuals/.110343|title=Kirakira Precure a la Mode Anime Reveals February 5 Debut, Theme Songs, New Visuals|date=December 26, 2016|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The opening theme is {{nihongo|\"SHINE!! Kirakira \u2606 PreCure a la Mode\"|SHINE\uff01\uff01\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9|SHINE\uff01\uff01 Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo}} by Yuri Komagata, while the ending theme for the first 22 episodes is {{nihongo|\"Let's La Cooking\u2606Showtime\"|\u30ec\u30c3\u30c4\u30fb\u30e9\u30fb\u30af\u30c3\u30ad\u30f3\u2606\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0|Rettsu Ra Kukkin \u2606 Sh\u014dtaimu}} by Kanako Miyamoto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinematoday.jp/page/N0088555|title=\u65b0\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u306f\u30d1\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30a8\uff01\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u00d7\u30a2\u30cb\u30de\u30eb\u5909\u8eab\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mynavi.jp/news/2016/12/26/021/|title=\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u6700\u65b0\u4f5c! \u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u3001\u6765\u5e742\u6708\u3088\u308a\u653e\u9001|first=Mynavi|last=Corporation|publisher=}}</ref> For the other 27 episodes, a second ending theme is used called {{nihongo|\"Shubidubi\u2606Sweets Time\"|\u30b7\u30e5\u30d3\u30c9\u30a5\u30d3\u2606\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0|Shubidubi \u2606 Su\u012btsu Taimu}} by Miyamoto. The music of the series is composed by [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] (''[[My Hero Academia]]'', ''[[Haiky\u016b!!]]'', ''[[Gundam Build Fighters]]''). The first single of the series was released on March 1, 2017 along with the first official soundtrack on May 31, 2017 titled ''Precure Sound Decoration!!''. A second official soundtrack for the series was released on November 29, 2017 with the title ''Precure Sound Go Round!!''. A vocal best album titled ''Suite\u2606Etude\u2606A La Mode'' was released on January 24, 2018, which featured songs from the anime and its movie.\n\n===Films===\nThe characters of the series appeared alongside characters from ''[[Go! Princess PreCure]]'' and ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'' in the crossover film, ''[[Pretty Cure Dream Stars!]]'', which was released in Japan on March 18, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-12/precure-dream-stars-film-announces-guest-cast-story/.110960|title=Precure Dream Stars! Film Announces Guest Cast, Story|author=|date=January 12, 2017|work=animenewsnetwork.com|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> A film based on the series, titled {{nihongo|''[[List_of_Pretty_Cure_films#Kirakira_PreCure_a_la_Mode_the_Movie:_Crisply!_The_Memory_of_Mille-feuille!_(2017)|KiraKira\u2606PreCure \u00e0 la Mode: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!]]''|\u6620\u753b \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9 \u30d1\u30ea\u30c3\u3068\uff01\u60f3\u3044\u51fa\u306e\u30df\u30eb\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30e6\uff01|Eiga Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo: Paritto! Omoide no Miruf\u012byu!}}, including a fully CG animated short titled {{nihongo|''Petit\u2606Dream Stars! Let's\u30fbla\u30fbCookin'? Showtime!''|Petit\u2606\u30c9\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba\uff01\u30ec\u30c3\u30c4\u30fb\u30e9\u30fb\u30af\u30c3\u30ad\u30f3\uff1f\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\uff01|Puchi \u2606 Dor\u012bmu Sut\u0101zu! Rettsu Ra Kukkin? Sh\u014dtaimu!}} was released on October 28, 2017.\n\n===Manga===\nThe manga adaptation of the anime was serialized in the March 2017 issue of [[Kodansha]]'s ''[[Nakayoshi]]'' magazine, written and illustrated by [[Futago Kamikita]] and ended serialization on December 29, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-29/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-manga-ends-in-december/.124605|title=Kirakira Precure a la Mode Manga Ends in December|work=Anime News Network|access-date=2018-02-24|language=en}}</ref> The first tank\u014dbon was released on August 10, 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/toeianime_shop/status/881714426281250817|title=\u2606\u66f8\u5f71\u89e3\u7981\u2606\u3010\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u3011\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u266a\u300c\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30ec\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f31\u7279\u88c5\u7248\uff0f\u901a\u5e38\u7248\u300d\u3054\u4e88\u7d04\u53d7\u4ed8\u4e2d\uff01\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb\u7279\u5178\u306e\u8a73\u7d30\u306f\u3082\u3046\u66ab\u304f\u304a\u5f85\u3061\u4e0b\u3055\u3044\u306d|last=\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7|first=|website=@toeianime_shop|language=ja|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> with the second released on March 13, 2018.\n\n{{Graphic novel list/header\n | Language = Japanese\n | WithTitle = no\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 1\n | OriginalRelDate = August 10, 2017\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-06-337866-5\n | LicensedRelDate = N/A\n | LicensedISBN = \n | ChapterList =\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 2\n | OriginalRelDate = March 13, 2018\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-06-511046-1\n | LicensedRelDate = N/A\n | LicensedISBN = \n | ChapterList =\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list/footer}}\n==Reception==\nIn their \"7 Great Gay and Lesbian Relationships In Anime\" feature, Crunchyroll compared the romantic relationship of Yukari Kotozume and Akira Kenjou, both female, to that of [[Sailor Neptune]] and [[Sailor Uranus]].<ref>http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2019/06/18/7-great-gay-and-lesbian-relationships-in-anime</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/}} at [[Toei Animation]] {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{ann|anime|18962}}\n* {{YouTube|channel = UCSsjL41NsyqSNNbanuI0htg|Pretty Cure official}}\n* {{Instagram|precure_alamode_animalsweets|Official Animal-sweets collections}}\n{{start box}}\n\n{{succession box|title=[[Pretty Cure]]|before=[[Witchy PreCure!]]\n|after=[[Hugtto! PreCure]] \n|years=2017-2018}}\n\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Pretty Cure}}\n{{Toei Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2017 anime television series]]\n[[Category:2018 Japanese television series endings]]\n[[Category:2017 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Cooking in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Magical girl anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Pretty Cure]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation television]]\n[[Category:TV Asahi shows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name = Kirakira \u2606 PreCure a la Mode\n| image = Kirakiraprec.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption  = Cover of the final [[Blu-ray]] volume, featuring the six Cures. In clockwise order: Cure Chocolat, Cure Macaron, Cure Custard, Cure Whip, Cure Parfait and Cure Gelato in the center. \n| ja_kanji = \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\n| ja_romaji = Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo\n| genre = [[Magical girl]]\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type = tv series\n| director = Kohei Kureta<br>Yukio Kaizawa\n| producer = Akira Tanaka<br>Risa End\u014d<br>Yu Kaminoki\n| writer = Jin Tanaka\n| music = [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]]\n| studio = [[Toei Animation]]\n| licensee = \n| network =  [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] ([[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], [[TV Asahi]])\n| network_en = \n| first = February 5, 2017\n| last = January 28, 2018\n| episodes = 49\n| episode_list = List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Izumi Todo]]\n| illustrator     = [[Futago Kamikita]]\n| publisher       = [[Kodansha]]\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014djo manga|Sh\u014djo]]''\n| imprint         = ''Wide KC''\n| magazine        = [[Nakayoshi]]\n| first           = March 2017\n| last            = December 2017\n| volumes         = 2\n| volume_list     =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = [[KiraKira PreCure \u00e0 la Mode: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!|Kirakira PreCure a la Mode the Movie: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!<br />Petit\u2606Dream Stars! Let's\u30fbla\u30fbCookin'? Showtime!]]\n| director        = \n| producer        =\n| studio          = [[Toei Animation]]\n| released        = October 28, 2017\n| runtime         =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Kirakira PreCure a la Mode'''''|\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9|Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo|lit. \"Glittering Pretty Cure [[List of French expressions in English|\u00e0 la Mode]]\"|lead=yes}}, shortened as {{nihongo|'''''PreAla'''''|\u30d7\u30ea\u30a2\u30e9|PuriAra}}<ref group=note>Shortened term Toei used in official [[Twitter]] posts of the anime</ref> is a 2017 Japanese [[magical girl]] [[anime]] series produced by [[Toei Animation]] and the fourteenth installment in [[Izumi Todo]]'s ''[[Pretty Cure]]'' [[metaseries]], featuring the twelfth generation of Cures. It is directed by Kohei Kureta and Yukio Kaizawa. Jin Tanaka wrote the script, and Marie Ino designed the characters. The cake and sweets designs were handled by [[Pastry chef|p\u00e2tissi\u00e8re]] Junko Fukuda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/toeianime_info/status/813128054574759936|title=\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u516c\u5f0f on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> The series began airing on all [[All-Nippon News Network]] stations in [[Japan]] on February 5, 2017, succeeding ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!|Witchy PreCure!]]'' in its initial timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anime.eiga.com/news/103897/|title=\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d17\u5e742\u67085\u65e5\u653e\u9001\u958b\u59cb\u3000\u30c6\u30fc\u30de\u306f\u300c\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u300d\u3068\u300c\u30a2\u30cb\u30de\u30eb\u300d|publisher=}}</ref>  It was then succeeded by ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'' on February 4, 2018. The series' main topic is happiness, while [[desserts]] and [[animals]] serve as the motif.\n\n==Plot==\n{{See also|List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode characters}}\nIchika Usami is a second year middle school student who loves sweets and wishes to work in a patisserie, but struggles to make anything good. One day, she encounters a fairy named Pekorin, who is able to detect \"kirakiraru\", an element residing in sweets that represent the feelings put into them. However, evil fairies start to steal the kirakiraru for themselves, leaving the sweets black and lifeless. Determined to protect the sweets, Ichika gains the power of the Legendary Patisserie and transforms into the Pretty Cure, Cure Whip, to protect the kirakiraru. Joined by five other Pretty Cures, Ichika opens up the mobile sweet shop, Kirakira Patisserie, and spends her days making sweets while fighting against those who seek to steal kirakiraru and bring misfortune to the world.<ref name=\"story\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/story/|title=\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30ea\u30fc\uff06\u30ad\u30fc\u30ef\u30fc\u30c9 - \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9-\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3:|publisher=Toei Animation|language=Japanese|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n==Production==\nThe series was first registered by Toei at the Japanese Copyright Office on October 25, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-10-25/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-trademark-filed/.108036|title='Kirakira Precure a la Mode' Trademark Filed|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> A month after registration, Toei opened a teaser site for the series with the catchphrase \"Create, Taste and Battle!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-27/toei-confirms-kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-tv-anime-for-2017/.109239|title=Toei Confirms Kirakira Precure a la Mode TV Anime for 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mantan-web.jp/2016/11/28/20161127dog00m200036000c.html|title=\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\uff1a\u7b2c14\u5f3e\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d\u304c17\u5e74\u6625\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30c8 \u3064\u304f\u3063\u3066\uff01\u305f\u3079\u3066\uff01\u305f\u305f\u304b\u3063\u3066\uff01|publisher=}}</ref> On December 26, 2016, Toei updated the official website with main characters and staff, alongside the two theme songs and the official release date, also marking as the third series in the franchise to utilize a 5-piece group. It was also confirmed that the main characters were all running a sweets shop<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moca-news.net/article/20161226/2016122606000a_/01/|title=TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u306f2\u67085\u65e5\uff08\u65e5\uff09\u653e\u9001\u958b\u59cb\u3002\u30ad\u30fc\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u30fb\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u8a2d\u5b9a\u306a\u3069\u3082\u89e3\u7981|publisher=moca}}</ref> and although it will still feature battle scenes like its predecessor, ''Kira Kira'' will have a different style of fight scenes called Colorful Pop Battles in order to fit with the series's theme.\n\nIn an interview with the team behind the series, they expressed a lot of concepts being used and adapted in the series. The producers stated that the 5-piece team concept was used after 10 years in order to differentiate it from the previous series, ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'' which uses the \"Buddy Concept\". The motif of the series was decided also by the producers due to the choices are being taken. Producer Yu Kaminoki said that \"Running a Sweets Shop/bakery is one of many girls have dreamed of when they grow up, and that is a good theme for the next series. However deciding on how fighting elements would fit in a Dessert-themed series is hard and is not compatible with Pretty Cure or any fighting girls series\" and also stated \"using Animals as a secondary morif could help balance the first motif of the series and is possible with imagination, to actually make the series work than just using Sweets as the series's motif\". Also, the producer said that \"Animal mofif would extend to the main character, Ichika, who decorates and creates desserts with an animal motif due to her huge imagination.\"<ref name=\"animate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1485843322&image_share=14|title=\u8089\u5f3e\u6226\u3092\u5c01\u5370\u3059\u308b\u3053\u3068\u3067\u63cf\u3051\u308b\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u3089\u3057\u3055\u304c\u3042\u308b\uff01\u3000\u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u795e\u6728\u512a\u30d7\u30ed\u30c7\u30e5\u30fc\u30b5\u30fc\uff06\u66ae\u7530\u516c\u5e73\uff33\uff24\uff06\u8c9d\u6fa4\u5e78\u7537\uff33\uff24\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|publisher=[[Animate]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile discussing the staff, the producer said that Kohei Kureta and Yukio Kaizawa were chosen to direct the series, as a way to lessen the burden in production due to coming up with newer concepts. Yukio Kaizawa was also chosen due to his work with ''Cure Flora and the Mischievous Mirror'' short film and that he said that he wanted to incorporate new ideas into the series as director. Kaizawa also stated that it was his first time to direct a series in Toei's Sunday morning lineup since joining the staff and that directing alongside Kohei Kureta would be a challenge. Kureta was grateful that he can work with him. Despite working together, both directors will direct the series in different episodes and both will have responsibility for how the series will turn out.<ref name=\"animate\"/>\n\nFor the characters, the staff made each of their personalities unique in order to match the animal motif of the series. The most unique one to stand out is Akira, in which the producers based her overall role to the {{nihongo|\"Otokoyaku|\u7537\u5f79||\"Male Role\"}} actresses of [[Takarazuka Revue]], a theatrical group owned by [[Hankyu Corporation]]. [[Nanako Mori]] said that her experience with the group in the past is the inspiration for her role in the anime and that playing a big sister in the series is a first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/news/2017020302.php|title=\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9 - \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9|author=|date=|work=toei-anim.co.jp|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n===Anime===\n{{see also|List of Kirakira PreCure a la Mode episodes}}\nThe anime began airing on [[All-Nippon News Network]] stations in Japan, including [[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] and [[TV Asahi]], on February 5, 2017, replacing the previous series, ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'', in its initial timeslot.<ref name=\"dateannounce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-25/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-anime-reveals-february-5-debut-theme-songs-new-visuals/.110343|title=Kirakira Precure a la Mode Anime Reveals February 5 Debut, Theme Songs, New Visuals|date=December 26, 2016|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The opening theme is {{nihongo|\"SHINE!! Kirakira \u2606 PreCure a la Mode\"|SHINE\uff01\uff01\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9|SHINE\uff01\uff01 Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo}} by Yuri Komagata, while the ending theme for the first 22 episodes is {{nihongo|\"Let's La Cooking\u2606Showtime\"|\u30ec\u30c3\u30c4\u30fb\u30e9\u30fb\u30af\u30c3\u30ad\u30f3\u2606\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0|Rettsu Ra Kukkin \u2606 Sh\u014dtaimu}} by Kanako Miyamoto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinematoday.jp/page/N0088555|title=\u65b0\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u306f\u30d1\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30a8\uff01\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u00d7\u30a2\u30cb\u30de\u30eb\u5909\u8eab\u300c\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300d|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mynavi.jp/news/2016/12/26/021/|title=\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u6700\u65b0\u4f5c! \u300e\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u300f\u3001\u6765\u5e742\u6708\u3088\u308a\u653e\u9001|first=Mynavi|last=Corporation|publisher=}}</ref> For the other 27 episodes, a second ending theme is used called {{nihongo|\"Shubidubi\u2606Sweets Time\"|\u30b7\u30e5\u30d3\u30c9\u30a5\u30d3\u2606\u30b9\u30a4\u30fc\u30c4\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0|Shubidubi \u2606 Su\u012btsu Taimu}} by Miyamoto. The music of the series is composed by [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] (''[[My Hero Academia]]'', ''[[Haiky\u016b!!]]'', ''[[Gundam Build Fighters]]''). The first single of the series was released on March 1, 2017 along with the first official soundtrack on May 31, 2017 titled ''Precure Sound Decoration!!''. A second official soundtrack for the series was released on November 29, 2017 with the title ''Precure Sound Go Round!!''. A vocal best album titled ''Suite\u2606Etude\u2606A La Mode'' was released on January 24, 2018, which featured songs from the anime and its movie.\n\n===Films===\nThe characters of the series appeared alongside characters from ''[[Go! Princess PreCure]]'' and ''[[Maho Girls PreCure!]]'' in the crossover film, ''[[Pretty Cure Dream Stars!]]'', which was released in Japan on March 18, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-12/precure-dream-stars-film-announces-guest-cast-story/.110960|title=Precure Dream Stars! Film Announces Guest Cast, Story|author=|date=January 12, 2017|work=animenewsnetwork.com|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> A film based on the series, titled {{nihongo|''[[List_of_Pretty_Cure_films#Kirakira_PreCure_a_la_Mode_the_Movie:_Crisply!_The_Memory_of_Mille-feuille!_(2017)|KiraKira\u2606PreCure \u00e0 la Mode: Crisply! The Memory of Mille-feuille!]]''|\u6620\u753b \u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9 \u30d1\u30ea\u30c3\u3068\uff01\u60f3\u3044\u51fa\u306e\u30df\u30eb\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30e6\uff01|Eiga Kirakira \u2606 Purikyua Ara M\u014ddo: Paritto! Omoide no Miruf\u012byu!}}, including a fully CG animated short titled {{nihongo|''Petit\u2606Dream Stars! Let's\u30fbla\u30fbCookin'? Showtime!''|Petit\u2606\u30c9\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba\uff01\u30ec\u30c3\u30c4\u30fb\u30e9\u30fb\u30af\u30c3\u30ad\u30f3\uff1f\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\uff01|Puchi \u2606 Dor\u012bmu Sut\u0101zu! Rettsu Ra Kukkin? Sh\u014dtaimu!}} was released on October 28, 2017.\n\n===Manga===\nThe manga adaptation of the anime was serialized in the March 2017 issue of [[Kodansha]]'s ''[[Nakayoshi]]'' magazine, written and illustrated by [[Futago Kamikita]] and ended serialization on December 29, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-29/kirakira-precure-a-la-mode-manga-ends-in-december/.124605|title=Kirakira Precure a la Mode Manga Ends in December|work=Anime News Network|access-date=2018-02-24|language=en}}</ref> The first tank\u014dbon was released on August 10, 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/toeianime_shop/status/881714426281250817|title=\u2606\u66f8\u5f71\u89e3\u7981\u2606\u3010\u30ad\u30e9\u30ad\u30e9\u2606\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30a2\u30e9\u30e2\u30fc\u30c9\u3011\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u266a\u300c\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30ec\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f31\u7279\u88c5\u7248\uff0f\u901a\u5e38\u7248\u300d\u3054\u4e88\u7d04\u53d7\u4ed8\u4e2d\uff01\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb\u7279\u5178\u306e\u8a73\u7d30\u306f\u3082\u3046\u66ab\u304f\u304a\u5f85\u3061\u4e0b\u3055\u3044\u306d|last=\u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7|first=|website=@toeianime_shop|language=ja|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> with the second released on March 13, 2018.\n\n{{Graphic novel list/header\n | Language = Japanese\n | WithTitle = no\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 1\n | OriginalRelDate = August 10, 2017\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-06-337866-5\n | LicensedRelDate = N/A\n | LicensedISBN = \n | ChapterList =\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 2\n | OriginalRelDate = March 13, 2018\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-06-511046-1\n | LicensedRelDate = N/A\n | LicensedISBN = \n | ChapterList =\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list/footer}}\n==Reception==\nIn their \"7 Great Gay and Lesbian Relationships In Anime\" feature, Crunchyroll compared the romantic relationship of Yukari Kotozume and Akira Kenjou, both female, to that of [[Sailor Neptune]] and [[Sailor Uranus]].<ref>http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2019/06/18/7-great-gay-and-lesbian-relationships-in-anime</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/precure_alamode/}} at [[Toei Animation]] {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{ann|anime|18962}}\n* {{YouTube|channel = UCSsjL41NsyqSNNbanuI0htg|Pretty Cure official}}\n* {{Instagram|precure_alamode_animalsweets|Official Animal-sweets collections}}\n{{start box}}\n\n{{succession box|title=[[Pretty Cure]]|before=[[Witchy PreCure!]]\n|after=[[Hugtto! PreCure]] \n|years=2017-2018}}\n\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Pretty Cure}}\n{{Toei Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2017 anime television series]]\n[[Category:2018 Japanese television series endings]]\n[[Category:2017 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Cooking in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Magical girl anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Pretty Cure]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation television]]\n[[Category:TV Asahi shows]]\n", "name_user": "Crboyer", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits byPuddleglum2.0(talk) to last version by 2601:155:8300:6E90:A040:CBB0:460D:4DA3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirakira_PreCure_a_la_Mode"}
